Advanced iPython: Images, plots, and widgets¶

Images¶

The easiest way to put an image into a notebook is to drag it into a markdown cell.

In [1]:
%cd ~/jupyter_examples

/gpfs/home/emwin/jupyter_examples

We can also use IPython.display to display images. Let's display a stickleback.

In [2]:
from IPython.display import Image
In [3]:
sticklepic = Image('stickleback.jpg')
In [4]:
display(sticklepic)

For manipulating images in Python, PIL is popular.

In [5]:
from PIL import Image
import numpy as np
img = np.asarray(Image.open('greta.png'))
In [6]:
img.shape
Out[6]:
(701, 640, 3)

And matplotlib is used for visualization.

In [7]:
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
In [8]:
plt.imshow(img)
Out[8]:
<matplotlib.image.AxesImage at 0x146b3b260440>

Let's load in an example MRI image.

In [9]:

In [11]:

In [12]:

import numpy as np

Interactions and observations¶

In [29]:
from ipywidgets import interact

Here's a very simple function that returns "Hello" + the input variable.

In [30]:
def f(x):
    return f'Hello {x}'

We can use interact to send our widget values to the function

In [31]:
interact(f, x=slider);

interactive(children=(IntSlider(value=0, description='x'), Output()), _dom_classes=('widget-interact',))

We don't even have to create the widget first. We can send it a default value and ipywidgets will guess the best widget for it. Try a string, a float, a bool, etc.

In [32]:
interact(f, x=100.0);

interactive(children=(FloatSlider(value=100.0, description='x', max=300.0, min=-100.0), Output()), _dom_classe…
To make two widgets interact with each other, use observe¶
In [33]:
size_slider = widgets.IntSlider(max = 600, value = 300)
greta = widgets.Image(value=image, format='png', width=size_slider)

def update_greta(change):
    greta.width = size_slider.value

size_slider.observe(update_greta, 'value')
In [34]:
display(size_slider)
display(greta)

Interactive graph plotting¶

In [35]:
selector = widgets.SelectMultiple(options=df.columns, value=[df.columns[0]])
rangeSlider = widgets.IntRangeSlider(max = len(df), value=(0, len(df)))

def myplot(columns, xrange):
    sns.lineplot(data=df[list(columns)].take(range(*xrange)))

interact(myplot, columns = selector, xrange=rangeSlider);

Interactive brain viewer¶

In [36]:
axis_radio = widgets.RadioButtons(options={'sagital':0, 'coronal':1, 'axial':2}, 
                                  description = 'Orientation',
                                  value=0)

slice_slider = widgets.IntSlider(max = brain_data.shape[0]-1, 
                                 description = 'Slice',
                                 value = brain_data.shape[0]/2)

def update_slider(change):
    slice_slider.max = brain_data.shape[int(axis_radio.value)]-1
    slice_slider.value =  brain_data.shape[int(axis_radio.value)]/2

axis_radio.observe(update_slider, 'value')

def brain_plot(slice_number, axis):
    brain_slice = brain_data.take(indices=slice_number, axis = axis)
    plt.axis('off')
    plt.imshow(np.rot90(brain_slice), cmap='gray')


interact(brain_plot, slice_number = slice_slider, axis=axis_radio);
